    {
      "id": "1123043829713485875",
      "type": "Reply",
      "timestamp": "2023-06-27T04:15:14.149+04:00",
      "timestampEdited": "2023-06-27T08:08:28.107+04:00",
      "callEndedTimestamp": null,
      "isPinned": false,
      "content": "Hi, @gregor. Thanks for your response. If I understand, what you mean is that whatever I hash within smart contract or zkProgram methods, needs to be always of a certain size, so you know the size and it's always the same, but what I want to do is being able to prove the size of files with different sizes. In order to create a proof that from an ordered set of files I serve ALL files that met the user's request criteria (therefore the user is getting the files the user wants, with a proof that when I serve their request, I do it without hiding any files and every file follows the user's request criteria)\n\nSo far I came up with using a merkle map where each key is the hash of a file, and each value is the hash of a Struct that contains the number of fixed-length pieces in which you slice the file, and also contains the value for the first piece. Then you can feed a zkProgram method with this Struct + the second piece, so the zkProgram outputs a proof that includes the result of hashing [first, second], a counter indicating the iteration number, and a Bool indicating if you already went through all the pieces (and the resulting hash equals the key), so you always have the certainty that if the value for a leaf in that merkle tree is set, you know the size of the file.",
      "author": {
        "id": "1050599472071180389",
        "name": "chrlyz",
        "discriminator": "0000",
        "nickname": "chrlyz",
        "color": "#FA7504",
        "isBot": false,
        "roles": [
          {
